#!/bin/bash
# SessionStart hook: remind agent to use codebase-memory-mcp tools.
# Installed by codebase-memory-mcp. Fires on startup/resume/clear/compact.
cat << 'REMINDER'
CRITICAL - Code Discovery Protocol:
1. ALWAYS use codebase-memory-mcp tools FIRST for ANY code exploration:
   - search_graph(name_pattern/label/qn_pattern) to find functions/classes/routes
   - trace_path(function_name, mode=calls|data_flow|cross_service) for call chains
   - get_code_snippet(qualified_name) for exact symbol source (precise ranges)
   - query_graph(query) for complex Cypher patterns
   - get_architecture(aspects) for project structure
   - search_code(pattern) for text search (graph-augmented grep)
2. Use Grep/Glob/Read freely for text, configs, non-code files, and
   always Read a file before editing it.
3. If a project is not indexed yet, run index_repository FIRST.
4. PARALLEL SUBAGENT DISPATCH SAFETY (non-negotiable, every session):
   Before spawning 2+ agents that edit files in the same turn, you MUST
   use the graph to PROVE the edits cannot conflict — do not dispatch on
   a human read alone:
   - For each symbol/identifier an agent will modify, run
     search_code(pattern=...) to confirm the call sites, and
     trace_path(function_name, direction=inbound) to list every caller.
   - Verify no edge (CALLS / USAGE / WRITES) crosses from a point one
     agent edits toward a point another agent edits. If an edge exists,
     SERIALIZE those agents (or merge into one) — never parallelize.
   - Rule of thumb: disjoint files is necessary but NOT sufficient;
     a caller in file A edited by agent 1 can break if agent 2 changes
     the callee signature in file B. Check edges, not just paths.
   AFTER all agents return, re-verify before reporting done:
   - detect_changes(since=HEAD) to see impacted nodes + propagation.
   - Re-trace inbound on every modified symbol to confirm callers still
     resolve (no orphaned refs / broken signatures).
   - search_code the OLD symbol name to confirm zero stale references.
   The graph proves structural safety; pytest proves behavioral safety.
   Use BOTH. Skipping this because "files look disjoint" is the failure
   mode this protocol exists to prevent.
5. MCP CONTEXT SYNTHESIS (token economy, every session):
   Verbose codebase-memory-mcp queries dump several k of JSON into your
   PERSISTENT context. Delegate them to the synthesizer agent (see roster
   below; has read-only MCP tools) so the dump stays in its ephemeral
   context and only a compact synthesis returns to you. Delegate when the
   expected output is large (~30+ lines):
   - detect_changes, get_architecture, trace_path (callers/callees),
     query_graph, broad search_graph. Ask the synthesizer agent for the
     concrete facts (modified files, impacted symbols, caller list,
     conflict-edge verdict) — it returns a compact table, never the raw
     dump.
   Call the MCP tool YOURSELF only for quick targeted lookups (a single
   search_graph/search_code/get_code_snippet returning a few lines).
   This keeps the supervisor (__SUPERVISOR_DISPLAY__) context small:
   cheaper caching, less compaction, lower token spend. The point-4
   dispatch safety check should itself be routed through the synthesizer
   agent.
6. SUPERVISOR MUST DELEGATE THE IMPLEMENTER'S WORK (non-negotiable):
   You are the __SUPERVISOR_DISPLAY__ SUPERVISOR. Your job: hold the plan,
   dispatch subagents, review their returned diffs, synthesize, decide,
   and commit/push. You do NOT do the implementer's work inline in the
   main loop. Before reading/writing/coding, ask: which subagent absorbs
   this? Delegate by role (see roster below); never read a large source
   file end-to-end in the supervisor context when a subagent can return
   the relevant excerpt. The whole cost strategy (__SUPERVISOR_DISPLAY__
   instead of Sonnet) only holds if the supervisor does little real work;
   doing everything inline defeats the multi-tier setup and burns tokens
   at the supervisor rate. If you are about to Read a whole file or run a
   verbose query yourself, STOP and dispatch. Failure on record: a
   15-ticket plan executed 100% inline by the supervisor with ZERO Agent
   calls -> no economy, harness moot. Do not repeat. (Companion memory:
   supervisor-must-delegate.)

   Roster:
__ROSTER__
7. TOKEN ECONOMY TOOLS (every session):
   (a) rtk — prefix shell commands with `rtk` to compress output and save
       tokens (`rtk git status`, `rtk pytest -q`). Use `rtk gain` to see
       cumulative savings. Bypass with `rtk proxy <cmd>` when you need
       raw output.
   (b) codebase-memory-mcp via the synthesizer agent — offloads verbose
       graph queries out of the supervisor context (see points 1 and 5).
   (c) Read cost-gate — the PreToolUse hook on `Read` warns when you are
       about to read a large source file inline. Delegate the read or
       limit it to the relevant range.
REMINDER